<paragraph id="106536C4A943FF85FF09FF50A050FE95" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">
Description (
<figureCitation id="88E12A41A943FF85FE9FFF50A2DDFF45" box="[337,464,152,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1828,1850]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,266,1787]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,261,1808]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Adults. 1. Xestia lanceolata sp. n., holotype, male, China, Yünnan (PGM); 2. Xestia lanceolata sp. n., paratype, male, China, Yünnan (PGM); 3. Xestia lanceolata sp. n., paratype, male, China, Yünnan (PGM); 4. Xestia diagrapha (Boursin, 1963), male, China, Sichuan (PGM); 5. Xestia diagrapha (Boursin, 1963), male, China, Sichuan (PGM); 6. Brachylomia pygmaea (Draudt, 1950), male, China, Sichuan (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608055/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">Figs. 1, 2, 3</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 
<quantity id="D7229B21A943FF85FD9BFF50A1C4FF45" box="[597,713,152,175]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="3" pageNumber="448" unit="mm" value="29.0" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="28.0">28–30 mm</quantity>
, length of forewing 
<quantity id="D7229B21A943FF85FC50FF50A719FF45" box="[926,1044,152,175]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="448" unit="mm" value="14.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="13.0">13–15 mm</quantity>
. Male. Antennae bipectinate, vesture of body and forewing ground colour variegate shaded grey, with a slight red-brown suffusion in specimens. The most remarkable external features of the new species are the pointed elongate forewing apex, the black basal dash, a more or less well discernible broad black definition of the prominent intercellular streak of the medial line, a more or less shallow claviform stigma, elongate grey orbicular and reniform stigmata, a wavy antemedial line, an arched—crenulate postmedial line, a slightly sinuous, fine, ochreous subterminal line, and a rather unicolorous, pale brown to greyish hindwing with a fine brown discal spot and pinkshaded grey setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="106536C4A943FF85FF09FE42A7A1FDE3" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">
The male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="88E12A41A943FF85FE68FE42A106FE4B" box="[422,523,394,417]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–10" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1898,1920]" captionTargetBox="[242,1336,336,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,330,1877]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–10. Male genitalia. 7. Xestia lanceolata sp. n., holotype, China, Yünnan, slide no. GYP4934 (PGM); 8. Xestia lanceolata sp. n., paratype, China, Yünnan, slide no. GYP4904 (PGM); 9. Xestia diagrapha (Boursin, 1963), China, Sichuan, slide no. GYP2376 (PGM); 10. Brachylomia pygmaea (Draudt, 1950), China, Sichuan, slide no. GYP4905 (PGM)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608057/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">Figs 7, 8</figureCitation>
) can be characterized by the strong, lanceolate, apically hooked uncus; an almost straight, basally broad, terminally slender harpe; a dorsally rounded cucullus section of the valva; and a fine pollex. The aedeagus is somewhat curved, the vesica broadly tubular and recurved dorsad with a conspicuous, robust, elongate, sclerotized bar, somewhat serrated dorsad, derived from the medio-dorsal section of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="106536C4A943FF85FF09FDDDA2A0FDC6" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,660]" box="[199,429,533,556]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">Female is not known.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="58C0654FA943FF85FF09FDFFA160FD9B" pageId="3" pageNumber="448" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="106536C4A943FF85FF09FDFFA160FD9B" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">
<emphasis id="22AEEAD6A943FF85FF09FDFFA25FFDA5" bold="true" box="[199,338,567,591]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">Distribution</emphasis>
. The four specimens have been found only in the high mountain region of 
<collectingRegion id="D21EF826A943FF85FB43FDF0A7E9FDA5" box="[1165,1252,568,591]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">Yünnan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="68CD7654A943FF85FB3FFDF0A63EFDA5" box="[1265,1331,568,591]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">China</collectingCountry>
, in 
<quantity id="D7229B21A943FF85FA93FDF0A3E7FD9B" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.65" metricValueMax="4.7" metricValueMin="4.6" pageId="3" pageNumber="448" unit="m" value="4650.0" valueMax="4700.0" valueMin="4600.0">4600- 4700 m</quantity>
, in the beginning of summer period.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="58C0654FA943FF85FF09FDB4A0A1FD7E" box="[199,940,636,660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="106536C4A943FF85FF09FDB4A0A1FD7E" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,660]" box="[199,940,636,660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">
<emphasis id="22AEEAD6A943FF85FF09FDB4A24DFD7E" bold="true" box="[199,320,636,660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="448">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific name indicates the robust, lanceolate uncus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
